[[ファイル:Tosen-jinja02s3200.jpg|thumb|250px|Haiden]]
'''Yusen Shrine''' (とうせんじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Arima-chō|Q18700495|WD=Q18700495|1=Arimachō}}, {{ill|lt=Kita-ku (Kobe)|Q1078814|WD=Q1078814|lt=Kita-ku|1=Kita-ku, Kobe}}, {{ill|lt=Kobe|Q48320|WD=Q48320|1=Kobe}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|WD=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}. It is also read "Onsen Jinja" and may be written {{ill|lt=Onsen Shrine|Q11562963|WD=Q11562963|1=Onsen Shrines}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha major shrine|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha major shrine|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system#other shrines|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=gōsha|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}.

=== History ===
Based on the tale that {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}} and {{ill|lt=Sukunabikona|Q3275687|WD=Q3275687|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona}} discovered Arima Onsen after seeing three {{ill|lt=crows|Q388450|WD=Q388450|lt=crows|1=Crow}} soaking in red hot water to heal leg injuries, these two deities are enshrined here, and three birds are carved on the haiden. Together with Kumano Kusumi-no-Mikoto, newly worshiped from the era of restoration of Arima Onsen by priest Ninsei beginning in {{ill|lt=1191|Q19738|WD=Q19738|1=1191}} ({{ill|lt=Kenkyū|Q1193933|WD=Q1193933|1=Kenkyū}} 2), they are called the "Three Guardian Deities."

Because the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}' records visits by {{ill|lt=Emperor Jomei|Q329761|WD=Q329761|1=Emperor Jomei}} and {{ill|lt=Emperor Kōtoku|Q317980|WD=Q317980|1=Emperor Kōtoku}}, and because it is listed among the 492 major shrines in the early-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, its high prestige in former times can be seen.

Formerly the shrine buildings (built in the mid-{{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, {{ill|lt=Kansei|Q1195131|WD=Q1195131|1=Kansei}} 10 / {{ill|lt=1798|Q7823|WD=Q7823|1=1798}}) stood in the precincts of {{ill|lt=Onsen-ji (Kobe)|Q11562943|WD=Q11562943|lt=Onsen-ji|1=Onsen-ji Temple}} at the foot of Mt. Atago, but in {{ill|lt=1885|Q7821|WD=Q7821|1=1885}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 18) they were moved to the current site on the middle slope of Mt. Atago. It was also ranked as {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

In front of Onsen-ji main hall there is a {{ill|lt=torii|Q234731|WD=Q234731|1=Torii}} and stone steps leading to the shrine buildings.

=== Shrine name ===
Some documents write it as Onsen Shrine, and proposed readings include "tōsen jinja," "tōzen jinja," and "yuno jinja," but today it is generally written "Yusen Shrine" and read "tōsen jinja." In the section for {{ill|lt=Arima District|Q11516836|WD=Q11516836|1=Arima district}} of {{ill|lt=Settsu Province|Q864163|WD=Q864163|1=Settsu Province}} in the 'Engishiki' Jinmyōchō, it is listed with {{ill|lt=Arima Shrine|Q11516720|WD=Q11516720|1=Arima Shrine}} and {{ill|lt=Kōchi Shrine|Q11392062|WD=Q11392062|1=Kuchi Shrine}} as "Yusen Shrine (yuno jinja)" [http://www.arima-onsen.com/facility_info113.html].

